# Meta Note: Exploration 003

## What worked

- Framing the task as a single theorem-facing balance audit was the right move. Once the exact question became "does the earlier slab appear anywhere in the identity?", the result was fast and decisive.
- Keeping the pair fixed prevented fake progress. The strategy did not waste another exploration searching for a different precursor family before asking whether the chosen pair had any exact memory principle at all.
- The structural negative was stronger than "no proof found." The later witness balance simply does not see the earlier slab.

## What to carry forward

- When a precursor is chosen from the same mechanism family as the event, the first quantitative test should ask whether the exact identity has any backward-memory term at all.
- If the answer is no, stop early unless there is a clearly named extra hypothesis worth making into a new mission.
- Backup quantities that are less directly tied to the witness channel should not be promoted after the main exact pair fails structurally unless they solve the structural defect, not just change vocabulary.

## Execution note

- The launched math-explorer also stalled after context loading. Manual recovery was easy because the decisive calculation was conceptual rather than computational: inspect the exact balance terms and ask whether `R_-` appears.

